{{Infobox language |name=Nhlangwini |altname= |nativename= |states=South Africa |extinct=? |ref=<ref name="Guthrie"/> |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] |fam6=[[Southern Bantu]] |fam7=[[Nguni languages|Nguni]] |fam8=[[Tekela languages|Tekela]] |iso3= |glotto=none |guthrie=S.405 }}
'''Nhlangwini''' (Hlangwane) is a Bantu language of [[South Africa]]. It is located along the border between Xhosa and Zulu, but is more closely related to [[Swazi language|Swazi]].
== References == {{reflist}} •Phyllis Jane Nonhlanhla Zungu, 1989, ''Nhlangwini, a Tekela-Nguni Dialect and Its Relationship to "standard Zulu" and Other Nguni Dialects'', University of Natal, Pietermaritzburg. {{Languages of South Africa}} [[Category:Languages of South Africa]] [[Category:Nguni languages]] {{Narrow Bantu languages|N-S}}
